<div class="sg">
  <h1>Midterm exam-1 study guide</h1>
  <p class="sub">Thursday, April 9, 2026 · Lecture 4 (Lab 2) + Lecture 5</p>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="sec-head l4">Lecture 4 — Lab 2: Office-Room Occupancy Prediction</div>
    <div class="cards">

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-green">Step 1</span> Data preprocessing — missing values (Cell 3)</div>
        <div class="item">Problem: <code>Light(lux)</code> had only 19,672 of 20,560 records — 888 missing values</div>
        <div class="item">Fix: <code>KNNImputer(n_neighbors=6)</code> — fills missing values using the mean of 6 nearest neighbors in feature space</div>
        <div class="item">Why KNN imputer (not simple mean): multivariate imputer — leverages relationships between features, not just the column alone</div>
        <div class="item">Order matters: handle missing values before encoding categoricals, otherwise NaNs get treated as a category</div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-green">Step 2</span> Data preprocessing — categorical encoding (Cell 4)</div>
        <div class="item">Problem: <code>date</code> column was object/DateTime type — not numeric, can't feed into ML</div>
        <div class="item">Fix: extracted only the <em>time</em> component (date part was nearly unique so not useful as a feature)</div>
        <div class="item">Encoded <code>Time</code> with <code>OrdinalEncoder(categories='auto')</code> — converts time strings to integer labels</div>
        <div class="item">Why not <code>LabelEncoder</code>: LabelEncoder sorts alphabetically first, potentially inflating numeric magnitude of later labels</div>
        <div class="item">Final column order: Time, Temperature(oC), Rel.Humidity(%), Light(lux), CO2(ppm), HumidityRatio(kg/kg), Occupancy</div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-green">Step 3</span> Data preprocessing — class imbalance / resampling (Cell 5)</div>
        <div class="item">Problem: <code>Occupancy</code> target was class-imbalanced (binary: 0 = unoccupied, 1 = occupied)</div>
        <div class="item">Fix: <code>SVMSMOTE</code> — SVM-based variant of SMOTE; generates new synthetic minority samples by interpolation (not duplication)</div>
        <div class="item"><code>sampling_strategy='not majority'</code>: oversample all classes except the majority until balanced</div>
        <div class="item">SMOTE vs. RandomOverSampler: SMOTE creates new synthetic points; RandomOverSampler just duplicates existing minority samples</div>
        <div class="item">SMOTE vs. ADASYN: both interpolate, but ADASYN adapts density — generates more samples in harder-to-learn boundary regions</div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-amber">Visualizations</span> Graphical previews (Cells 6 & 7)</div>
        <div class="item"><strong>Histograms (Cell 6)</strong> — showed skewed/asymmetric distributions for most features (except <code>Time</code>); this motivates non-linear normalization later</div>
        <div class="item"><strong>Scatter matrix (Cell 7)</strong> — pairwise scatter plots of all 7 features; diagonal shows KDE density curves</div>
        <div class="item"><strong>Scatter plot: Temperature vs. Light colored by Occupancy</strong> — rooms tend to be occupied when both temperature and light are high; this confirms those features are predictive</div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-green">Step 4</span> Feature engineering — identification (Cell 8)</div>
        <div class="item">Cast entire dataset to <code>float64</code> for numerical consistency</div>
        <div class="item">Separated inputs (<code>feats_X</code>): 6 columns — Time, Temperature, Humidity, Light, CO2, HumidityRatio</div>
        <div class="item">Separated output (<code>trgt_y</code>): 1 column — Occupancy</div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-green">Step 5</span> Feature engineering — generation/creation (Cell 9)</div>
        <div class="item">Created 4 new composite features to capture non-linear relationships:</div>
        <div class="item"><code>humidity</code> = Rel.Humidity(%) × HumidityRatio — combined humidity measure</div>
        <div class="item"><code>co2_per_temp</code> = CO2(ppm) / Temperature — CO2 relative to thermal state</div>
        <div class="item"><code>light_per_temp</code> = Light(lux) / Temperature — light adjusted for temperature</div>
        <div class="item"><code>temp_per_humidity</code> = Temperature / Rel.Humidity(%) — thermal-humidity ratio</div>
        <div class="item">Checked for <code>NaN</code> or <code>inf</code> values introduced by division (e.g. divide-by-zero edge cases)</div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-green">Step 6</span> Feature engineering — selection (Cell 10)</div>
        <div class="item"><code>SelectKBest(score_func=f_classif, k=8)</code> — selects top 8 features by F-statistic (ANOVA): measures how well each feature separates the classes</div>
        <div class="item">Correlation heatmap using Kendall's tau (non-linear correlation) — identifies multicollinearity/redundancy among selected features</div>
        <div class="item">Goal: keep features with high correlation to target but low inter-feature correlation</div>
        <div class="item">Final features selected: Temperature(oC), Rel.Humidity(%), Light(lux), CO2(ppm), co2_per_temp, light_per_temp (6 features)</div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-green">Step 7</span> Train/test split (Cell 11)</div>
        <div class="item"><code>StratifiedShuffleSplit(n_splits=1, test_size=0.2, train_size=0.8)</code></div>
        <div class="item">Stratified: ensures train and test sets contain proportional class representation from <code>Occupancy</code></div>
        <div class="item">80% training, 20% test</div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-green">Step 8</span> Feature scaling/normalization (Cell 12)</div>
        <div class="item">Because histograms showed skewed data, used <code>QuantileTransformer(output_distribution='uniform')</code></div>
        <div class="item">Transforms skewed/congested feature distributions into a uniform [0,1] distribution — a non-linear transformation</div>
        <div class="item">Fit ONLY on <code>X_train</code>, then transform both train and test — prevents data leakage from test into training</div>
        <div class="item">Alternatives shown (commented out): <code>MinMaxScaler</code> (linear, range scaling) and <code>Normalizer</code> (L2 row-wise scaling)</div>
        <div class="item">Target <code>y</code> was not scaled — classification labels (0/1) don't need normalization</div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-amber">Performance evaluation — training (Cell 14)</span></div>
        <div class="item">3-fold cross-validation on training data: <code>cross_val_predict(..., cv=3)</code></div>
        <div class="item">Algorithm used: KNN (<code>KNeighborsClassifier</code>) wrapped in <code>MultiOutputClassifier</code></div>
        <div class="formula">
          ACCURACY  = (TP + TN) / (TP + TN + FP + FN)<br>
          PRECISION = TP / (TP + FP)<br>
          RECALL    = TP / (TP + FN)<br>
          F1-SCORE  = 2 × (PRECISION × RECALL) / (PRECISION + RECALL)<br>
          AUC-ROC   = area under TPR vs. FPR curve  [0, 0.5, +1 → worst, random, perfect]<br>
          MCC       = (TP×TN − FP×FN) / √[(TP+FP)(TP+FN)(TN+FP)(TN+FN)]  ∈ [−1, +1]
        </div>
        <div class="item"><code>average='weighted'</code>: computes precision/recall/F1 per class then averages, weighted by number of true instances per class</div>
        <div class="item">MCC is robust to class imbalance — more reliable than accuracy alone when classes are unequal in size</div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-amber">Performance evaluation — testing (Cell 15)</span></div>
        <div class="item">Final model retrained on full training set, then evaluated on held-out test set</div>
        <div class="item">Same 6 metrics computed: Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1-Score, AUC-ROC, MCC</div>
        <div class="item">Confusion matrix plotted with seaborn heatmap — rows = groundtruth labels, cols = predicted labels</div>
        <div class="item">Overfitting check: Train ERR &lt;&lt; Test ERR → overfit; Train ERR &gt;&gt; Test ERR → underfit</div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="divider"></div>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="sec-head l5">Lecture 5 — Deep Learning & ANN</div>
    <div class="cards">

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-blue">Artificial neuron structure</span></div>
        <div class="item">Inputs: x₁, x₂, …, xₙ — the raw data fed into the neuron</div>
        <div class="item">Weights: w₁, w₂, …, wₙ — learned values that scale each input</div>
        <div class="item">Net input: X = Σ xᵢwᵢ = x₁w₁ + x₂w₂ + … + xₙwₙ</div>
        <div class="item">Activation function: f() — introduces non-linearity</div>
        <div class="item">Net output: y = f(X) = f(Σ xᵢwᵢ)</div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-blue">Two major ANN topologies</span></div>
        <div class="two-col">
          <div>
            <div class="item" style="font-weight:500;color:var(--color-text-primary);padding-left:0">Feed-forward (FfNN)</div>
            <div class="item">Signals flow in one direction only (input → output)</div>
            <div class="item">No feedback loops</div>
            <div class="item">Single-layer: no hidden layers</div>
            <div class="item">Multi-layer: 1+ hidden layers</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="item" style="font-weight:500;color:var(--color-text-primary);padding-left:0">Feed-back (FbNN)</div>
            <div class="item">Signals flow bidirectionally</div>
            <div class="item">Has feedback loops — output can feed back to earlier layers</div>
            <div class="item">Basis for RNNs and LSTMs</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-blue">Activation functions</span></div>
        <div class="formula">
Linear/Identity:    y = x  (no nonlinearity; can't backpropagate)<br>
Sigmoid/Logistic:   y = 1 / (1 + e⁻ˣ)  → [0, 1]  (vanishing gradient)<br>
Tanh:               y = (1−e⁻²ˣ)/(1+e⁻²ˣ)  → [−1, +1]  (vanishing gradient)<br>
ReLU:               y = max(0, x)  → [0, x]  (dead neuron risk)<br>
Leaky ReLU:         y = max(ax, x), a ∈ [0.01, 0.4]  (reduces dead neurons)<br>
Softmax:            y = eˣⁱ / Σ eˣʲ  → [0,1]  (multi-class probabilities)
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-blue">DL vs. ANN comparison</span></div>
        <div class="two-col">
          <div>
            <div class="item" style="font-weight:500;color:var(--color-text-primary);padding-left:0">Deep Learning (DL)</div>
            <div class="item">Automatic feature extraction (Feature/Representation Learning)</div>
            <div class="item">3+ hidden layers</div>
            <div class="item">More neurons per layer</div>
            <div class="item">More complex layer connections</div>
            <div class="item">Requires more training time</div>
            <div class="item">Needs GPUs/TPUs</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="item" style="font-weight:500;color:var(--color-text-primary);padding-left:0">ANN (shallow)</div>
            <div class="item">Manual feature engineering required</div>
            <div class="item">0+ hidden layers</div>
            <div class="item">Fewer neurons per layer</div>
            <div class="item">Simpler connections</div>
            <div class="item">Faster training</div>
            <div class="item">Runs on CPUs</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="warn">All DL networks are ANNs, but not all ANNs are DL networks.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-blue">Training strategies — feed forward pass</span></div>
        <div class="item">Computes the net input and net output for every neuron in sequence, layer by layer</div>
        <div class="item">Net input for a neuron in next layer: x<sup>l+k</sup>ᵢ = Σⁿⱼ₌₁ w<sup>l</sup>ᵢⱼ x<sup>l</sup>ⱼ + 1·b<sup>l</sup>ᵢ</div>
        <div class="item">Net output: y<sup>l+k</sup>ᵢ = f(x<sup>l+k</sup>ᵢ) where f is the activation function</div>
        <div class="item">l = current layer, k = step to next layer, i = node in next layer, j = node in current layer</div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-blue">Training strategies — gradient descent</span></div>
        <div class="item">Goal: find the global minimum m of the error function E, where ∇m = 0</div>
        <div class="item">Iteratively steps down the slope — negative slope descends toward minimum</div>
        <div class="formula">
w_new = w_old − η·(∂E/∂w)   [weight update]<br>
b_new = b_old − η·(∂E/∂b)   [bias update]<br>
η = learning rate;  ∂E/∂w = ∇ = gradient
        </div>
        <div class="item">−ve slope → descending toward minimum; +ve slope → ascending away from minimum</div>
        <div class="item">Repeated until gradient reaches 0 (global minimum)</div>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title"><span class="badge badge-blue">Training strategies — backpropagation (feed backward pass)</span></div>
        <div class="item">Realized via gradient descent — propagates error backward through the network</div>
        <div class="item">Three-tuple error chain: FB/BP = (E₁, E₂, E₃)</div>
        <div class="item">Full gradient via chain rule:</div>
        <div class="formula">∂E/∂w<sup>l</sup>ᵢⱼ = (∂E/∂y<sup>l+k</sup>ᵢ) · (∂y<sup>l+k</sup>ᵢ/∂x<sup>l+k</sup>ᵢ) · (∂x<sup>l+k</sup>ᵢ/∂w<sup>l</sup>ᵢⱼ)</div>
        <div class="item">E₁ term: −1(T − y<sup>l+k</sup>ᵢ) — error from target vs. output</div>
        <div class="item">E₂ term: y<sup>l+k</sup>ᵢ · (1 − y<sup>l+k</sup>ᵢ) — sigmoid derivative</div>
        <div class="item">E₃ term: x<sup>l</sup>ⱼ — the input to the weight (product rule)</div>
        <div class="item">Combined: ∂E/∂w<sup>l</sup>ᵢⱼ = −1(T − y<sup>l+k</sup>ᵢ) · y<sup>l+k</sup>ᵢ · (1 − y<sup>l+k</sup>ᵢ) · x<sup>l</sup>ⱼ</div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="warn" style="margin-top:1rem;font-size:13px">
    Exam tip: know when each metric is most appropriate — MCC for imbalanced datasets, AUC-ROC for ranking ability, F1 when precision and recall both matter. Also be ready to identify TP/FP/TN/FN from a confusion matrix scenario.
  </div>
